8d097d3c-6df1-4e62-82bb-b0ae0664807b.157f66e5-8e6e-40b0-adcf-97f27711eb7d.prompt=Enter a value for json 8d097d3c-6df1-4e62-82bb-b0ae0664807b.2718b6b8-4116-4ba2-89d4-cbde3907dd29.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and and
creates and populates a flow variable for each member in the object.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA".  This operation
would create the flow variables city and state with the values "Palo Alto" and
"CA".

A optional prefix string can be specified that will be prepended to each flow
variable that is created.  For example, if the prefix is set to "my.", then
then the above object would result in the variables my.city (with value "Palo
Alto") and my.state (with value "CA").  This can be useful if flow variables
already exist with the given names to avoid overwriting their values.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object that will be converted into flow variables.  The
      operation will return a failure if the it is not a JavaScript object.

   prefix
      The prefix to prepend to each flow variable name that will be created.
      This is useful for creating unique variable names.

Responses

   success
      The flow variables were successfully created from the object.

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation.  You may wish to use a
      tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   A separate output will be created for each member of the object.  Each of
   these outputs may in turn contain another object or array.
8d097d3c-6df1-4e62-82bb-b0ae0664807b.60651cad-257b-4412-84b7-ba9c3948de5e.description=
This flow sends, stores or displays a notification message according to your notification type selection. You can use this flow to select how to be notified about the outcome of other flows. 

Inputs\:
    notifyData -  The content of the notification message.
    notifyMethod - The notification type. This value is not case sensitive.
Valid values\: Write to File, Email, Display or None
    subject - A summary of the notification content. 
    destination - The destination of the notification. You must specify a value for this input if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’ or ‘Write to File’.
Valid values\: An email address or a file name
    notificationServer - The email server used to send the notification email message. If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    from - The email address of the sender of the notification email message.  If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    serverPort - The notification service’s server port. This field’s value is used when the "notifyMethod" is ‘Email’, but it is optional.
Default value\: 25
    htmlEmail - The value should be true if the email is in rich text/HTML format. The value should be false to send the email in plain text format.
Default value\: true

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
    To schedule a flow that uses this flow, you need to supply all the required fields for the used notification method. For example, if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘File’, the "destination" input must also be specified.

Examples\:
    This is a valid input example for storing a notification message to a file\:
      notifyData\: notificationContent
      notifyMethod\: Write to File
      subject\: notificationSubject
      destination\: C\:\Program File\notification.txt
8d097d3c-6df1-4e62-82bb-b0ae0664807b.6a7fb6af-553d-4c4a-915c-5faae73d1788.description=


Inputs\:
    url - The REST API base url.
    username - The username used for URL authentication.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no autentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. There client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need and you can specify only one.
Default value\: basic
Valid values\: basic, digest, ntlm, kerberos, any, ""
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the "proxyUsername" input value.
    paramCompany - Quoted company to search for.

Results\:
    returnResult - This will contain the response entity (unless destinationFile is specified). In case of an error this output will contain the error mesage.
    FailureMessage - The final error message returned to the user.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
8d097d3c-6df1-4e62-82bb-b0ae0664807b.8845a684-0d01-4ebb-be21-2e42e7514d42.description=
This operation takes a reference to JSON (in the form of a string) and runs a specified JSON Path query on it. It returns the results as a JSON Object. 

Inputs\:
    json - The JSON in the form of a string.
    jsonPathQuery - The JSON Path query to run. See details and examples in the Notes section below.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the resulted JSON from the given path.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
1.Query syntax\:
JSONPath 		Description
------------                           -------------     
$ 		The root object/element
@ 		The current object/element
. or [] 		Child operator
n/a 		Parent operator
.. 		Recursive descent. JSONPath borrows this syntax from E4X.
* 		Wildcard. All objects/elements regardless of their names.
n/a 		Attribute access. JSON structures do not have attributes.
[] 		Subscript operator. XPath uses it to iterate over element collections and for predicates. In Javascript and JSON it is the native array operator.
[,] 		Union operator in XPath results in a combination of node sets. JSONPath allows alternate names or array indices as a set.
[start\:end\:step] 	Array slice operator borrowed from ES4.
?() 		Applies a filter (script) expression.
() 		Sript expression, using the underlying script engine.

2.Examples\:
The examples below use the following JSON string value\:
{
    "store"\: {
        "book"\: [
            {
                "category"\: "reference",
                "author"\: "Nigel Rees",
                "title"\: "Sayings of the Century",
                "price"\: 8.95
            },
            {
                "category"\: "fiction",
                "author"\: "Evelyn Waugh",
                "title"\: "Sword of Honour",
                "price"\: 12.99
            },
            {
                "category"\: "fiction",
                "author"\: "Herman Melville",
                "title"\: "Moby Dick",
                "isbn"\: "0-553-21311-3",
                "price"\: 8.99
            },
            {
                "category"\: "fiction",
                "author"\: "J. R. R. Tolkien",
                "title"\: "The Lord of the Rings",
                "isbn"\: "0-395-19395-8",
                "price"\: 22.99
            }
        ],
        "bicycle"\: {
            "color"\: "red",
            "price"\: null
        }
    },
    "expensive"\: "10"
}

JSONPath 			Result
------------                                                ---------
$.store.book[*].author 		The authors of all books in the store
$...author 			All authors\: ["Nigel Rees","Evelyn Waugh","Herman Melville","J. R. R. Tolkien"]
$.store.* 			All items in store, which are some books and a red bicycle.
$.store..price 		The price of everything in the store
$..book[2] 			The third book
$..book[(@.length-1)] or $..book[-1\:] 	The last book in order
$..book[0,1] or $..book[\:2] 	The first two books
$..book[?(@.isbn)] 		Filter all books with isbn number
$..book[?(@.price<10)] 		Filter all books wholse price is less than 10
$..* 			All Elements in XML document. All members of JSON structure. 
$.store.book[0]		Returns the details of the first book\: reference,Nigel Rees,Sayings of the Century,8.95
$.store.bicycle			Returns the details of the bicycle including null in JSON format\: {"color"\:"red","price"\:null}
